        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down</placeName>
                    <date>March 16.</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
                    <p>It is <hi rend="underline">extremely</hi> kind of you to have sent me the fresh packet of good seeds, some of which I have just put on damp sand to germinate. I tried the former lot on damp sand and damp earth, (and the remainder are now in water!) and all became a sheet of mould, so that I was in despair of even one germinating. Your note shows me that the case is even more curious than I before understood.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> I am, however, at present overwhelmed with the number of experiments in hand. But Ægilops must not be neglected.</p>
<p>Yours much obliged | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            </div>
            
            
            <div type="footnotes">
                <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11423.xml">letter from A. S. Wilson, 14 March 1878</ref>.</note>
                <note xml:id="foot.f2">Wilson had sent a box of seeds of <hi rend="italic">Aegilops ovata</hi> (a synonym of <hi rend="italic">A. geniculata</hi>, ovate goatgrass) with his <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11381.xml">letter of 28 February 1878</ref>, and more with his <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11423.xml">letter of 14 March 1878</ref>. Wilson had observed that only seeds from the middle floret of a spikelet would germinate (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11423.xml">letter from A. S. Wilson, 14 March 1878</ref>). </note>
            </div> 
     
